The Diet of an Obese Child: Doesn't Take Breakfast and Takes Sausage for Dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 years have problems with overweight, 9% of schoolchildren will be above average weight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which human beings are evolving and the models that surround them are.
On the tables of obese children, for example, cold meats are found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had chips at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of large children, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case of most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from Czech primary schools.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the decisive factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight and even obese children is the lack of proper diet and insufficient physical exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed indicate, for example, eating breakfast five times a day - in case - lunch - tasting - dinner, which is a basic principle of a good diet," one of the results of the survey said.
Without breakfast and cold meats at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the families of students eat at the same time.
In the majority of families each eats their breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been noted is that a tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned exercise regularly but for parents it is about half, only 15%.
Prepare Your Food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diets from the possibilities proposed according to their own taste and personal opinion.
“The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating.”
Among their favorite dishes are plenty of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is in particular a high preference for sugary lemonades," the results of the survey said.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading for Health
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
“During a control of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’ awareness session, there was a determined willingness to move towards healthy eating,” the results of the survey indicate.
The most striking was, for example, with regard to sugary lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread or potato flour balls).
