IBM History: From the slices of cheese to the robberies in the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York 100 years ago; it originally had the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 – originally a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the year 80 of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 presided over the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of the firm - it was on Watson's ideas that the identity and culture of the company were built up to now.
Watson headed the Kusqu' firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In Watson's first four years, revenue increased to $9 million and the company began to expand to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who held the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight to the Moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began dealing with consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has succeeded at IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
IBM recently developed a “Smarter Commerce” platform that helps salespeople manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in our territory as well.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that deals with speech recognition.
