21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion that Moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a happy end: the Austrian pavilion for world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, glass sheds, lively and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels is a good and famous example of this.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its light and suspended steel and glass construction.
Construction is considered to this day as an important milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian World Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it eventually became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the world exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the southern railway station of Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for as long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and increasingly decayed.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "House of the 21st century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a shot of luck from any point of view.
The new beginning was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she has particularly carried out the work of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments, and she has obtained public funds.
Except for contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his move to Vienna and its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "an energy gulf," Krischanitz says.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, fiberglass reinforced insulating glass was laid and the roof replaced by a special safety glass.
Thermal bridge beams were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings were rehabilitated.
Two basements made room for the new operation, a panel of dimmed light between the house and the road ensures lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - this is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remained, the house is painted in a rust-protective shade of red-brown color.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for the monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also please the office of protection monuments," Krischanitz says and he draws attention to a crude soil underground.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and lightweight.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, “which came from Brussels,” Krischanitz said recently, a typical “Drop-in-the-City” story.
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the 21st-century house is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the newly planned "neighborhood of the central station", with offices and apartments.
And perhaps another lucky move will happen: the 21st century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
