Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity, titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that hold your heart.
A tip to get started: carefully rip this page and make it your bookmark.
In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the fog of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "an anti-history work."
It includes a few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and materials.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like." We find in it the "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance workers and vendors.
Some will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war. Some will lose limbs, go crazy or lose their lives.
Their lives wander here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are reignited.
Peter Englund’s book deviates from traditional history books.
It denies the idea that the First World War can only be summed up by the terrible trench war on the Western front.
"Beauty and grief" skillfully describes other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; a Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; Tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina smelling cordite.
When cannon blows sound in the distance, and you are a house mother, do you stay or are you fleeing?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been enhanced by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them talk about deprivation and the ability to get out of it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, überall ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It continues on replacement food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a fake wood bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
It states that "837 permitted substitute meats are registered in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories address honor and courage.
One American acknowledges his own drive towards savagery and declares about war: "You feel that after all, that's what men were meant for, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that there's no empese behind it.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is in danger of dying, and that no one will notice or pay attention to it.
“When you are resigned to sacrifice, you hope to have an audience,” he wrote.
This is unfortunately rather comparable to "a convicted man strangled in secret."
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
