Walls Have Eyes: Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far-right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy sharing his anti-immigration opinions online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to being caught in a deadly madness in Norway in July leaving 77 victims, was faced with his first trial.
While Breivik was acting alone, he was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time leading up to the attack on his computer, chatting with a few of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to find them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is packed with so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific precision — the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett’s team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. They targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. Questions asked were about their level of education, their attitudes towards violence, and their optimism about their own future.
By getting in touch with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that touch on health issues such as social trends, thanks to “Like”, wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three contents per day, the “data supernova” generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research work whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach on the street.
“Before, when you were trying to conduct investigations into people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You had to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to come in,” Bartlett said.
“Facebook avoids all of this – you have direct access to their information.”
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and colleagues, young students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook were considerably more likely to be alcoholics than discreet students.
Megan Moreno suggests that student colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and eventually intervene to help a student whose status would too often talk about alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would not otherwise be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics on the love situation and Valentine's Day, the turnout rate in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available - digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its treasure trove of data available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, there is something else online.
"I don't think a large number of users have ever thought of the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things,” Selwyn said.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and pen are still the best tools to use.
“Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people,” he says.
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and the social is not in front of a computer."
