7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some have compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will air this week in the first part of a film on major markets, is how well this creative mind understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders were suffering from a "great illness that makes them think that a great idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates an idea.
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat down for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years since Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple, already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in transport.
It was only after Steve Jobs’ death that a full video was found in the director’s garage.
This video, slightly elevated, is the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will air in theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him elbows to speed him up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, we find a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them then the implementations immediately.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“Throughout all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues to elaborate on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - it often starts with a "standard cost" assessed at first glance and then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a turn at the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that used to hack phone networks and call for free over long distances.
The device has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball of different things half a dozen times and you screamed in the public phone and it happened to you a minute later at the public phone next door,” Jobs says, laughing.
“We were young and with this Blue Box we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn’t both know much, but we invented a little thing capable of controlling great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to recount a wonderful ride he and Wozniak have come up with: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s demarche):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a phone call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and how employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP’s employees to visit the company’s research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first desktop ever designed.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a glance.
Early in his career, as he settles down to sell a few PCBs, a customer asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some big fights... they screamed at me that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that proved incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are breathing out:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would be mistaken and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you worked at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copy machine or a better printer, and then?"
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing can evolve it, so [these are these kinds of people] that end up leading businesses and product-specialized staff are put away from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product versus a bad product - the required manual labor.
This is what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire IT industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They snatched defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge part of manual work separates a brilliant idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about his subtleties.
There are compromises to be made... Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made out of personal taste. It's about trying to expose you to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
This is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it were not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dine with opponents of health law as court meets
The day the Supreme Court meets behind closed doors to discuss the issue of political disagreement, whether opposition to President Obama’s health law will be heard, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were noticed at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will defend the case in the high court.
The event took place last Thursday, when the nine judges met for a conference to discuss the petitions for consideration.
One of the cases in question involved a 26-state trial challenging the ambitious health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that was a rallying point for conservative activists nationwide.
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, because a monumental 5:30 argument is expected next March, and the result will likely be likely to promote the destabilization of the 2012 presidential race, which will be booming by the time the court’s decision is rendered.
The lawyer who will stand before the court and argue against the rejection of the law will likely be Paul Clement, who served as solicitor general of the United States during the George W. Bush administration.
Clément’s law firm, PLLC Bancroft, was among the two dozen law firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group dedicated to upholding conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another proponent was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which presents a huge financial stake in the outcome of the dispute.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court conference on the case.
It included Mitch McConnell, a top Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health law.
The star guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
This is not new: the two judges have been present at the events of the Federalist Society for years.
And there is nothing that goes against the rules of ethics.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would arguably argue by the Code of Canon 4C, which states: "A judge may attend fundraisers from organizations related to law and others although the judge cannot be an intervener, an honorary guest, or appearing on the program of such an event."
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas in the vicinity of two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm government ethics activists.
“This violation of ethics and superb indifference to the code contradicts statements by several judges that the Court abides by the same rules applicable to all other federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were drinking and dining and at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have pending cases in court."
Their presence and participation in the fundraising of this event removes any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little regard for critics claiming that they too easily mix court affairs with the agenda of groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a high-profile conservative activist.
Moreover, the Conservatives claim that it is Justice Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was solicitor general of the Obama administration when the first oppositions to the law were brought to the level of the court of first instance.
Her critics pressured Kagan to refuse to hear the case, saying she had been too involved in defending the law to be impartial.
Kagan gave no indication that she would.
