Severe Pentagon warnings about potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta raised pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon corridors to Afghanistan’s battlefields, including gatherings of civilians.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 or more cuts is imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
“The impacts of these reductions would be devastating for the ministry,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said the failure of Congress to reach a budgetary agreement resulting in so-called sequestration would result in 23% reductions as well as the freezing of many new projects.
“Such a significant reduction, applied indiscriminately, would make most of our ships and construction projects unexecutable — you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or vessel — and severely undermine other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote.
"We would also be forced to separate from a number of our civilian personnel and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we should almost certainly send civilians on leave without pay in order to achieve the goal."
"These changes would shake the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparedness."
The reductions would eventually affect the fighting troops, continues Panetta.
"Although wartime financing of foreign contingency operations accounts is not directly affected by sequestration, war efforts would be negatively affected by serious disruption to core budgets," Panetta said.
"The contracting staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in contracts and oversight of contracts that support the war."
“Staff managing wages would be reduced, resulting in delays in payments to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details about the potential impact of automatic compressions on the Department of Defense.
“The consequence of a sequestration on the Department of Defense would have triggered a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world leader of military power.”
