“It’s not a consequence we can live with, and it’s certainly not the one we should impose on ourselves.”
“Sequestration is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent warnings from senators increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon from reductions remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible cuts, even though he himself reached the Pentagon’s highest position accumulating years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and knowing he was facing difficult choices.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a dark picture of what could happen - a soldier with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a brigade without bullets."
"It's a fighter jet without enough trained pilots."
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don’t have enough trained soldiers capable of accomplishing the mission,” Panetta said in his preliminary remarks to the Pentagon.
“It’s a depressed force, unprepared and unable to deal with potential opponents.”
"De facto, she calls for aggression."
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how further reductions could “generate significant operational risks: delays in response to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limitations on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and assumed unacceptable risk in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could move to the couperet, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a new planned bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy Humvee.
Ending the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is an essential step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines shows how pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has been billed as an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of campaign funding violations related to covering an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legionary.
There have been instances where teachers have given test responses to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we meet?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout: "I got you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research of such projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the research findings is that the earliest myths about lying have been debunked.
The liars look you in the eye.
They do not stutter, blush or shake.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the statement structure, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast and still emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are adept at reading others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more “centered” lies while women tell more “centered” lies—usually to protect someone’s feelings—that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called “establishing the benchmark data.”
This helps provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally shakes their feet constantly so as not to throw unfair accusations when you see them shake their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues to verbal and non-verbal misleading behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Misleading people can immobilize the upper body when trying to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly, or present post-interview relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a posture change when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview response.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
Famous Scott Peterson slipped off using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Misleading individuals may also use distant language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or fully repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember right... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
