The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, according to the rate of unemployment in the state during the first three quarters of the year has been observed an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 signanoens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent to the second quarter of the population.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly depending on the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we observe is a rise in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who make dollars in an illicit way it is not easy that they work to earn them, that they invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes said the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people leaving the state to go abroad to work in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of entry difficulties and secondly because when entering they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people stay here and ask for work sources, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
According to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the employed population in the state work there without paying contributions as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Aside from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for lag for the state is low wages, the entity has the lowest pay in the country, according to the registries of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly income of the workers of Signano was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which lies at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Aside from declining economic activity and rising unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the State FDI reached $630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent from the previous year of the same $5 million 143,312 recorded.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the Government of the State requested in July at the public congress the approval of a loan of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the congress of the State was 2,600 trillion pesos and no savings were observed until November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the employers' sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés' government demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the economy of Sinaloa during this year was really very poor, we have to work intensively to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our effort, we had to align the effort of all and especially the good work already synchronized of this new government team, hopefully next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts at the beginning of the year held back the state’s economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, among which frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state to productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms, we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa is unlocked," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channeled the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to deliver good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the management of public policy.
