The Court validates the "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogous cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, because the radio and television regulations are reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favour of the project only voted Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero same.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Representatives have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the implementation of the decree and all the actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of ministers also resolved to reject the complaint made by the House of Representatives, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister-President said that he disagreed with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also do not consider that if he did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of state leadership.
The substitution of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this translates into better radio spectrum exploitation, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitalisation that involves a decision in the public interest that not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, includes a group of powers that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they had the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress in a form, for it ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assured.
