"Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to perform one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group asserts that for them it will also be a dream come true to happen in this country.
Bassist and founding member Jeff Ament ensured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The band is in the South American wing of its two-decade work celebration tour and will make its one-stop stop in Central America on Sunday.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles band The X and the Las Robertas nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will be happening in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I only stayed in Costa Rica once the holidays; it is such a beautiful country and I think we will be able to spend a few days there.
We are excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is some kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What is your message to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying beside us for all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to be spent until this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add some pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve offered over the past 21 years have taken place over the past two weeks.
We have offered two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope it has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle; for both, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of friends surfers and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned, through the people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you aves offered huge shows, with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never produced ourselves there, we have no restrictions as to what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is the reason for this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone loves different songs, which is why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to perform each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t performed in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and why we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don’t think any of us ever imagined that we were going to be a great rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it feel like a dream.
We continue to recount our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together thrills us a lot.
We love each other and we love creating music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of large groups.
We are very close friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
“Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to still be friends with them all and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours stands together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that’s a lot longer than many bands normally last.
Firstly, I believe we are all lucky to be still alive and secondly, we all care for others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don’t spend too much time touring because it’s easy to fall into this game from large crowds and people who love your music.
If you don't forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we must respect the music and what brought it, without thinking of the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which is not really interested in any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
