The Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome communicates the details of the air accident in which lost his life the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) informed that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly against the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the impact zone do not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In research, it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was structurally present.
“The helicopter had been designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements for carrying them.
The floor had a pane of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For now, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can take a few months, it can even take a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Managing Director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that the moment of impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and this happened on a soft ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, TBS holder Pérez Jácome listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aviation regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM mentioned adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced to the boundary area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-rise layers of cloudiness.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions the crew sought a lower height area and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably prior to the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remnants in a reduced area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The dispersion model of the aircraft remains makes it possible to assume that the helicopter hit the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
At the site of the disaster there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple ground contacts.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9 thousand 200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disarticulated himself along his journey.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful search in a wider area than the encircled area, around the accident, no dispersed parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Insurance conducts an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called the 'genetic protocol of obesity of children and adolescents' that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry at the Specialty Hospital of the 20th Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
During the investigation, people with or without rights are invited to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence for minors is made every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sportive Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sportive Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the purpose of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young people in Mexico to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific dietary questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (seeking to identify people associated with childhood obesity) will be applied to all participants.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity for boys and 47 percent for girls; when it comes to overweight, there was also a dramatic increase," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others by its genetic history.
On average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American, 30 percent European and five percent African inheritance, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, doctors give it to the parents in writing, explaining each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - cornmeal meat paste wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 blackcurrants each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the construction and maintenance of the same bituminous pavement is adequate, blackcurrants could be reduced.
During his conference A Technology Opinion on Blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture having characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and consequently, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating forces, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If modified asphalt were to be used, it would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the layer of asphalt, he says, one puts a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material of which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first that gets spoiled is the rolling film and only subsequently is affected the layer of asphalt, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrant and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
