Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A Cali-based fingerprinter went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4 a fingerprinter from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprinters working in the local offices of the ITC, this week was the "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking adequate courses, he specialized in fingerprinting, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for her.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who ran the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigative team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galton magnifying glass, ink, a collector and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a typist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know about our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying the corpses, fingerprinters support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher said that in a case of theft he had to remove a part of the wall of a house, because in this place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas to get a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the full-handed fingerprint and identify the offender who participated in different robberies,” he recalls.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be suspect of the crime and indeed a print on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it puts him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprinter explained that “fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents” are being extracted.
When they appear, a collector or strip is used to collect them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the declining database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers," said the CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything that is touched does not necessarily become a footprint.
It can be used, however, if the necessary confrontation is made.
The ‘indignant’ defies the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters rushed in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
A large part of the people accessed the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The Occupy Wall Street movement on Tuesday challenged New York authorities by trying to re-enter, through a court order, Manhattan Square, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another Big Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were rushing in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order that allows the “indignant” to camp again in that place, while the other part of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new arrests.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will move to another place and continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful protests,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the “indignant” response to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Justice Lucy Billings issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the place and allowed protesters to stay in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignant' occupied a new park at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue power stations, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some protesters, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization says there are hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene in their behalf in front of the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned enclosure - remains closed pending the celebration of a judicial hearing scheduled for Tuesday, during which the legality of this morning's evacuation is to be analyzed.
A few displaced protesters were carrying and distributing copies of this court order at that time and even handing it over to officers monitoring the place, causing "certain small clashes," Bray said, who denounced the fact that some officials beat the protesters.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or from enforcing “laws published after the occupation began or from barring protesters from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they used before.”
Mayor Bloomberg told reporters that because of this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and to protesters, but he warned them that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councillor personally defended the evacuation at dawn in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to harm other people," because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"This morning's evacuation at dawn was disgusting and demonstrates that Bloomberg is deeply more interested in defending financial interests than those of American workers," the movement's spokesman said, accusing the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression."
Occupy Wall Street officials also said they did not plan to organize "big actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions to commemorate the two-month protests, which began on Sept. 17.
