Japan reborn after earthquake
GDP rises by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescing after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe in Japan since World War II.
Early estimates by the Government of Tokyo have estimated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have subsided.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, Gross Domestic Product data between July and September was used to turn the page definitively: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualized rate.
The one recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes, in addition, the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that calls for the crisis to take advantage of to consolidate – or rebuild – infrastructure, to use shortfalls to grow from scratch.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo recovered to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "safe haven values" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the forecast turmoil of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, made the yen contribution responsible for their weak results between July and September.
While markets continue to be based in the EU’s peripheral countries, the Yoshihiko Noda Government does not lower its guard.
"We need to monitor the persistent risks, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of flooding in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy, said yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) noted that the majority of member countries in September showed clearer signs of economic slowdown.
The indicator anticipating the tipping points of the global economy has highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
Because it dropped four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The Eurozone has even been below the average, which is in level 100, n decreasing eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
