A measure that is likely to provoke anger, but would bring in 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, of more symbolic scope: to impose on civil servants a day of leave without compensation in the event of a work stoppage (they have so far no leave period, compared to three days in the private sector).
While these issues are being discussed, the majority also relaunches the theme of fraud, this time targeting abuses related to work stoppages.
"The checks are going to be much larger and, in addition, if you are taken, you will pay back," Xavier Bertrand told RTL on Sunday.
As in other cases, the advertising effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
It has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives since 2002, most of which have paid off.
The French are no more sick than elsewhere in Europe.
Let’s look at the national figures first.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than 237 million euros of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditures in 2008, at 11.3 billion euros.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and occupational accidents, and 54% concerned sick leave, or € 6.2 billion.
That means 2.5% of health expenditures.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days of work stoppage, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that hides certain differences: another survey, published in 2007 by career management website Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any sick days.
Another study, this time from Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more prone to work stoppages than elsewhere.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) in France ranged between 10% and 11%, compared to 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sick leave fraud represents very little in the face of black work.
As for fraud, it reaches only a small extent.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 has meant that checks are systematic on sick leave of more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 short-term stops were "unjustified or too long", i.e. 37,050 cases.
In the case of systematically controlled breaks of more than 45 days, there were 11% of "inadequate or unjustified" cases out of 1.2 million, or 132,000.
In total, therefore, 169,000 "unjustified" cases, out of several million employees who had had a sick leave.
A figure that represents very little compared to, for example, that of black work.
According to UMP member Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, this would represent 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, which is more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud to the latter.
