Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, according to Royal Society of Canada report
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements for this.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to be made by a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has spawned a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada report.
And despite most Canadians’ desire to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, in Quebec, this rate is the highest, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on incompetent or non-consensual persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signer of the report, said in a teleconference yesterday, there would be more cases of these overflows precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," Downie said.
Canadians support euthanasia
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would help end-of-life people ease their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid survey.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people are of less value.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing patient care, the situation is less clear, the report authors say.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it should be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect a denial of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Finally, with respect to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee calls for it to be considered when it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and to be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already raised concerns about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada expert report.
Dr Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts signing the report "extreme", inter alia because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to terminally ill patients.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who would be tired of life and who would be over 18 years of age could ask for help in suicide," said Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
“In society,” he says, “there are beacons and constraints.”
