Austria is thus responding to a request from the Eurozone summit in Brussels on 26 October: the Heads of State and Government had then called for the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The system adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", with Germany being the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural government deficit will have to decrease annually by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, as of 2017, the federal government’s structural government deficit will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to put the public debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
