Energy policy:
The facts must outweigh the dogmas.
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with from short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is indeed energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy that an election rendezvous is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that nuclear holds in them.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will result in a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless it deprives a huge part of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is neither the case with Belgium, which makes it necessary to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor with Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation of power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are continuing their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to its park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island crash.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence exacerbated by the increased use of imported gas, in particular from Russia, a surge in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal power plants.
Within a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated on.
European champion of wind, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; by virtue of which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a pledge for the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear would result in a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful statements on the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not manifest a principled opposition to this energy, polls show.
The energy policy of our country has helped build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it drives a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and makes them very job-creating non-relocable.
If France decides to exit nuclear, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros of annual French exports of nuclear equipment and services as a skin of grief.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer is scheduled?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miraculous electricity production, nor is there any diabolical one.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville construction site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human errors caused the drama.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two unprecedented natural disasters that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR has a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians eager to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift given to Areva and EDF competitors by leaving them the way to seize leadership in the inescapable development of nuclear.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the number policy, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus between left and right.
To the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising almost 2 million immigrant workers", and to the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confines himself to trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally paying off; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries.
Restricting immigration anemia to growth and deteriorate employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants are likely to replace national workers, especially low-skilled workers, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mostly engaged in jobs in sectors where there is a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the more skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow job supply.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in long-term real wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the US Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenues minus expenditure) of €150,000 to public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the term, to go look for the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe Invented Democracy, European Democracy Remains to Think
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would suffice for democracy to definitively triumph over its enemies to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
It is known, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much, first of all, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the genuinely false Greek referendum in this respect will have had the value of a double revealer: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to necessity and in a dispersed order.
A white-seing to the absolute European monarch or a leap together in the void of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cutters, but a common, legal, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal - there is nowhere else to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
The whole of Europe is bowing to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to restore the leadership of the European project to popular sovereignty.
Because together, Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless of course it leads to disaster.
After long fighting this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic government.
Oh, well.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new impasse.
We must take a new step in European integration.
In order to make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The revolution in interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European sovereignty of the people.
To make Europe, let’s make Europeans.
