It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for Sharia law while its activists engage in the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are primarily concerned with churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active, increasing attacks on police stations.
Abuja’s reaction is, as usual, without nuances.
The army is invading the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on the sect will radicalize and leave its northern fiefs.
Last Christmas, she claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked the police headquarters in Abuja in a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the United Nations headquarters will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria is now a concern for all security experts.
While Aqmi has invested in Mali and Niger, and al-Chebab Somalians are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat to the heart of the continent.
Last week, during an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned Boko Haram and said he was willing to “share all the information.”
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
On China, Iran, aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete for simplicity and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by crisis manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
By listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been multiplying the thunderous foreign policy statements and shortcuts, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often unsupported - are fused.
Mitt Romney, best placed in the race for the nomination of the "Grand Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and challenge them "for manipulation of their currency", a theme carried in an America exasperated by the migration of entire parts of its industry to Asia.
No matter if it involves the start of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, former Obama ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated foreign policy vision, nearly choked himself in the face of an attitude that “flattens” emotions.
He called for a muscular but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who is stagnant in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Like Reagan
Romney also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
“If I am elected, I will stop Iran,” he boasted.
“If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb.”
He also pledged to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to that partner.
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, shows an embarrassing ignorance of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is "trying to develop nuclear capability" - apparently ignorant of the fact that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to engage the US military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from 2008 Republican candidate John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president reply that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine in anti-terrorism matters.
They rightly insist on the failure of its naïve dialogue with Iran, on the overly hasty departure of the “boys” from Iraq, on its distortions in Libya, thus sticking to it a label of weak.
But the attack is not so easy.
The population considers Obama’s national security record, which eliminated bin Laden, rather positive.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to stalemate.
And, arguing that America needs to be economically rebuilt to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more justly.
The Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe to Russia on the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event brightly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia with Germany under the sea, on Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and fine buffet.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the region of St. Petersburg to the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site looks like a victory.
The project had been heavily contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any overland passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a little bit of their power: it becomes harder for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut it off access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has triumphed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-consuming and declining Western countries.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically,” Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed by inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how politically and economically large gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of steel sheathed concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“One hundred had to be abducted or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect the fauna and flora have also had to be multiplied.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts along its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project officials renounced it when the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company settle permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who predicted the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for outdoor observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, wide of one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters seconds, it delivers precise information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
There are 200 bars at the start and 100 bars at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transmission capacity to the company for 20 renewable years.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided for 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back into their expenses, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every passing hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, of hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, takes care of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has restored to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robot portrait of the buyer, because the notebook attracts both the businessman, the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its inception, now has almost 100 employees and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
“We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition " Detour " where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendar, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a whole range of supports.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a voluntary public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
"No," said <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, managing director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
“The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.”
At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.
“There is still a lot to be done.”
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before entering employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it difficult to return to work, and that "constitute the node of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's the objective brakes.
There remains the unspoken, the mentalities that are evolving, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entrepreneur for the City indicated that the managers interviewed had a "low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled ".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, dating from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, to 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
